    "## Abstract\n",
    "\n",
    "Obesity rates all across America are often blamed on fast food access, but is this assumption properly supported by data? Our project investigates whether fast-food restaurant density at the county level correlates with adult obesity rates. We utilized data from the USDA Food Environment Atlas and CDC PLACES to build a reliable dataset covering 2,947 U.S. counties, capturing fast-food density, grocery store density, median household income, and adult physical inactivity rates. Different from our analysis however, fast-food density only managed to show a weak negative correlation with obesity (r=-0.18), which only explains just 3% of county level differences in obesity rates. Overall, our findings suggest that lifestyle and socioeconomic conditions show that physical inactivity was the strongest single predictor, followed by median household income. This comes to show that fast food access alone is not the primary driver of obesity at the county level.\n"
   ]
  },
  {
